<br>  Posts: 531<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/23/02 9:46:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3485.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: KS? followed by Ninja act</span><hr size=1> Kerryn where did I mention anyone's here's grammar specifically?<br>
<br>
Alkan, as far as I can tell, did nothing wrong, aside from a reather unfortunate typo, which I have already apologized for not recognizing as such.<br>
<br>
The entire incident at hand here is Riaan's perceptions and actions. And I think I removed myself from an opinion on those.<br>
<br>
Yes, I stand by my disposition to judge the value of peoples opinions by their use of language. In my opinion, less literate people are less educated and have less material available to form a solid opinion. They are not stupid because they cannot write eloquently. <br>
<br>
Does that mean I assume people who use 'ur' are less intelligent? No. It doesnt even mean that I think their opinion is crap. I look at the whole of their use of language, not just the grammar or the spelling.<br>
<br>
A sufficiently intelligent person can be less literate and less educated and still have a strong and valid opinion. I don't apply a negative value to the opinion of someone because they cannot write with well formed sentances and conjugate their verbs correctly. But, I do apply a positive value to people who can express themselves clearly with a degree of eloquence. Since the number of people I apply a positive value to is approximately five, and the rest of the people are neutral, I don't see that as making me a bigot. Its not like only five people on this board are right and everyone else is wrong.<br>
<br>
I can usually tell a thirteen year olds post from someone whose literary skill have not developed since the sixth grade, and I would probably assess more value to the opinions of the older, wiser individual.<br>
<br>
But the true measure of how much value I put into someone's opinion comes from how close to my own opinion it is. And If I feel a need to argue an opinion I will do so based on the facts used to support that opinion, not based on the language used to present the opinion.<br>
<br>
However, an eloquent presentation of facts and opinions will bear more weight than a jumble of d00dsp34k. If I am alone in this view, I would be shocked.<br>
<br>
And in reality, some people out there will read a well written, eloquent post, in my style, and feel as if they are being spoken down to, and will favor people whose verbal presentation most resembles their own style. Sadly, I was not gifted enough in my social skills to maintain dialogue in the vernacular. Heck, in some areas of the country I think the vernacular is not even a variant of english anymore.<br>
<br>
Ryn, I am no more a bigot for favoring people who write with eloqence than you are for judging me for something I never said I did.<br>
<br>
At no time did I directly reference Alkan's grammatical skills.<br>
<br>
There is a large difference between a grammatical error and a typo. And had I recognized it as a typo, I would never have posted on this thread.<br>
<br>
You are reading more between the lines than is there. Any negative opinion I had of Alkan or his opinion, was based on the belief that he was an ignorant racist. And I have already explained and apologized for not checking my keyboard...<br>
<br>
Now, Ryn, if you feel the need to continue calling me names...please do. <br>
<br>
Elitist would be the first one you should pick, but that would be merely you judging me based on my usage of the language.<br>
